g.text: Talks like a duck, but has
As an extra or props in a movie.
A spy uses the real object, but notices its
moves, and records them and can interfere in any interaction.
You need a concrete class to spy on, and have that do some of the real work.
Note that the order of teaching and invocation is different,
when you want the spy to stand in for the real object.
See the mockito documentation for the reason.
Spying, however thrilling it might sound, should
be used sparingly. A proper testable design can help avoid it.
as far as SUT is concerned
